<header class="header">
  <h1>Fruit Sling vs Net Bag for Trellised Melons</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Both options support heavy melons on a trellis, but they behave very differently as the fruit grows.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most home gardeners, fruit slings provide more adjustable, gentle support, while net bags are simpler and work well for smaller melons or quick setups.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Growing melons vertically saves space and improves airflow, but it creates one major challenge: the fruit becomes too heavy for the vine to support on its own.
  </p>
  <p>
    Both fruit slings and net bags solve this problem, but choosing the right one depends on how large your melons are and how you manage your trellis system.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: Which Is Better?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> fruit slings for larger melons and adjustable support.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for simplicity:</strong> net bags for quick, easy setups.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for airflow:</strong> both work, but slings tend to be less restrictive.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The main difference is control vs convenience.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Fruit Slings Do Better</h2>

  <p>
    Fruit slings are designed to cradle the melon from below, distributing weight evenly without constricting the fruit as it grows.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>adjustable positioning as fruit grows</li>
    <li>less pressure on the rind</li>
    <li>better for large or irregular shapes</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    They are especially useful for heavier melons that would otherwise stress the vine.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Net Bags Do Better</h2>

  <p>
    Net bags are simple and quick to use. You place the fruit inside and tie the bag to your support system.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>fast to install</li>
    <li>low cost</li>
    <li>minimal adjustment needed</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    They work well for smaller melons or when you want a simple, repeatable setup.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Key Differences</h2>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Feature</th>
          <th>Fruit Sling</th>
          <th>Net Bag</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Support style</strong></td>
          <td>Cradles fruit from below</td>
          <td>Encases fruit</td>
        </tr>
