          <td>Moderate if tight</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When to Use a Fruit Sling</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Large melons:</strong> cantaloupe, muskmelon, or heavier varieties.</li>
    <li><strong>Long growing periods:</strong> when fruit size increases significantly.</li>
    <li><strong>Careful management:</strong> when you want precise support.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Slings give you more control as the fruit develops.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When to Use a Net Bag</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Small melons:</strong> compact or quick-growing varieties.</li>
    <li><strong>Simple setups:</strong> minimal adjustment needed.</li>
    <li><strong>Multiple plants:</strong> easier to scale across many fruits.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Net bags are a practical choice when convenience matters more than precision.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Waiting Too Long to Support Fruit</h3>
  <p>
    Once the vine is already stressed, support is less effective.
  </p>

  <h3>Using Bags That Are Too Tight</h3>
  <p>
    This can restrict growth or create pressure points on the fruit.
  </p>

  <h3>Not Matching Support to Fruit Size</h3>
  <p>
    Larger melons often need more adjustable support than net bags provide.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How This Fits Into a Trellis System</h2>

  <p>
    Both slings and net bags attach to your existing trellis or support line. The effectiveness depends on how stable that structure is and how evenly weight is distributed.
  </p>

  <p>
    Strong vertical support combined with proper fruit support prevents both vine damage and fruit loss.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Best Fit by Growing Setup</h2>

  <div class="scenarioGrid">
    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Vertical Trellises</h3>
      <p>
        Fruit slings provide more stable support for heavier melons.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Small Garden Spaces</h3>
      <p>
        Net bags allow quick support across multiple plants.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Large Melon Varieties</h3>
      <p>
        Slings reduce stress on both fruit and vine.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Low-Maintenance Setups</h3>
      <p>
        Net bags require less adjustment over time.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Use</h2>

  <p>
    For most trellised melon setups, use fruit slings if you are growing larger melons or want better control over support. Use net bags if you are growing smaller varieties or want a faster, simpler setup.
  </p>

  <p>
    In many cases, a mix of both works well depending on fruit size and plant vigor.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Match the support to the size of the melon, not just the convenience of the tool.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    Fruit slings and net bags both support trellised melons, but they serve slightly different purposes.
  </p>

  <p>
    Slings offer better adjustability and support for larger fruit, while net bags provide a simpler, faster solution for smaller melons. Choosing the right option depends on how much control you want and how large your fruit will grow.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Use slings for control, and net bags for convenience.
  </p>
</section>